<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-425-462  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 425 462.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  May 1 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>12 year-old cited in computer fraud case.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>McMullen, Barbara E.; McMullen, John F.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   TRW Inc. (crimes against).andO;Ticker:    TRW.andO;Topic:     Computer industryComputer hackersInvestigationsLegal IssuesTheft of InformationChildrenMichigan. State Police DepartmentLaw Enforcement.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>12 YEAR-OLD CITED IN COMPUTER FRAUD CASE GROSSE ILE, MICHIGAN, U.S.A, 1990APR 27 (NB) -- A twelve-year-old Grosse Ile boy is the prime focus of aninvestigation by the joint state-federal Michigan Computer Crime Task Forceinvolving illegal computer entry into the giant TRW electronic database.andM;The boy, a seventh-grade student, is said to have lifted credit card numbersand information from the database and then posted them on computer bulletinboards.andP;  The information was then allegedly widely used by readers of thebulletin boards for purchases and telephone calls.andM;Although earlier wire service reports stated that the 12-year old wasarrested, John Britt a special agent with the U.S.andP;  Secret Service office inDetroit, told Newsbytes that this was not the case, &quot;What actually happenedwas that during the execution of a search warrant at the home of the boy,computer equipment was seized for further investigation.andP;  That investigationis on-going.andP;  The decision regarding filing of charges against the youth willbe made by the Michigan State Police.&quot;andM;Britt added the search action was a result of previous arrests, tip-offs andTRW's discovery of the breach in its security.andM;The youth's mother was quoted as saying that the family was stunned by theincident.andP;  She said that her son excels in math and geography and normallyspent four to five hours each weeknight and fourteen hours a day on theweekends using the computer.andP;  &quot;He didn't bother me,&quot; she said.andP;  &quot;He sat thereon his computer.andP;  Well, I figured, computers, that's the thing of the day.&quot;andM;Another Secret Service source explained to Newsbytes that its involvement inthe investigation is a result of a 1984 federal regulation that gaveresponsibility to the Secret Service for computer fraud, &quot;Under US CodeStatute 1030, we now have the nationwide responsibility for investigatingthese activities and we work closely with the local authorities in theseactions.&quot;andM;(Barbara E. McMullen andamp; John F. McMullen/19900428)</TEXT></DOC>